Suppose you want to create a class for which only a single instance (or object) should be
 created and that single object can be used by all other classes. So , here we can use Singleton
 Design Pattern . So we can say that when only one object is to be created and
shared among different classes then we use Singleton Design Pattern.


The Lifecycle of Eager Initialization
Class Loading: When the JVM first encounters the SingletonEager class (usually when you reference it in Main), it loads the bytecode.

Static Initialization: During loading, the JVM allocates memory for all static variables. It executes new SingletonEager(), which calls the constructor and prints your "object created" message.

Memory Residency: That single object now sits in the Metaspace/Heap for the remainder of the program's life.

The Method Call: When you call getInstance(), you aren't "getting a new object"; you are simply getting a pointer (reference) to that one object that was created in Step 2.

Thread Safety: This is "automatically" thread-safe. Java guarantees that static initializers are handled correctly even if multiple threads try to access the class at the exact same time.

Performance: getInstance() is lightning fast because it just returns a reference; it never has to perform a check like if (instance == null).

The "Eager" Downside: If this class is very "heavy" (uses lots of memory or connects to a database) and you don't end up actually using it, you’ve wasted resources because it created itself the moment the class was loaded.

